cells: My lettering scheme for all piece types is similar to Speffz but the order of the faces is U-F-R-B-L-D instead.
I'm the Finnish NR holder for MBLD (25/25), 3BLD (25.91 single, 34.31 mean) and 5BLD (8:55).
There might be some simple algs that are not exactly speed-optimal for me
There are spots for FU-xy edge flips in the sheet, I will fill these up as I'm learning more algs. These are marked with cyan.
Some algs that were particularly hard for me to learn/remember or otherwise illogical are marked with green. (also the ones that are new to me)
In many algs, moves cancel into wide moves (e.g. R M2 -> Rw M'). They are marked with light yellow.
RUf algs are marked separately with red.
The worst algs are in bright yellow, I need to optimise them soon.
I'm regularly checking the list and learning some new algs.
For parity, after executing edges I use a 2e2e alg solve the last (odd) target and swap UB-UL at the same time.
The list might not be completely optimal, but a lot better than some time ago.
When I was starting with FU edges, I used this "parity alg" for for most targets:
Lw U' L' U M' U' L U M L' (has the same principle as M2 parity alg: setup the last target to UB without messing the M slice, do M', undo setup, do parity alg)
The algs in the cells are for 4BLD.
Hover over the cells to see some some alternative algs, some of them are are useful for 5BLD, later I'll distinguish the 5BLD algs clearly.
Don't use this at the moment, just don't
I'm filling this up with pretty easy algs first and speed-optimize later.
